## Pattern Classification

Your code matches **two** patterns from the migration guide:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| **Timeout enforcement** | `thread.Abort()` after `Join(timeout)` fails | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort to continue** | `catch (ThreadAbortException) { Thread.ResetAbort(); }` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always wrap in using
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run replaces manual Thread creation
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

            // WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the token fires
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls for This Migration

| Pitfall | Details |
|---|---|
| **Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive** | `Thread.Abort` forcibly injected an exception anywhere in the thread. `CancellationToken` does nothing unless the work checks it. If `work` is a tight CPU loop or a blocking synchronous call that never checks the token, it will **keep running** after the timeout. |
| **Fire-and-forget work keeps running** | When `WaitAsync` throws on timeout, the `Task.Run` work continues in the background. The old code killed the thread; the new code abandons it. If this is unacceptable, `work` must accept and check a `CancellationToken`. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks an internal timer. The `using` statement above handles this. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures we only catch our own timeout, not an unrelated cancellation from inside `work`. |

## If `work` Must Actually Stop on Timeout

Pass the token through so work can cooperate:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then check the token at regular checkpoints:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

## If Work Is Truly Uncooperative (Can't Be Modified)

Move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill` on timeout — that's the only .NET 8 equivalent to the old forcible termination.

## What Was Removed

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (implicit via timeout) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed — no equivalent needed |
